Today, I am disgusted by Senate Republican‚Äôs vote on the Motion to Proceed to Calendar #120, H.R. 1628, the American Health Care Act of 2017. With this vote, Senate Republicans have begun the process of taking away health care from millions of Americans.   There will be many amendments and changes over the next 20 hours as the Senate begins its process but the basic facts underlying Republican repeal efforts have not changed. At least 22 million Americans will lose health coverage; health insurance premiums will rise; patient cost sharing will increase; and patient protections will no longer exist.  The 50 Republican Senators plus Vice President Pence know they voted for these heinous provisions when they voted for the Motion to Proceed. They willingly voted to destroy the health of the American people and I will do everything in my power to hold them accountable.

This morning, President Trump conducted his latest policy roll out via Twitter this time assaulting our brave transgender service members. Although it remains to be seen how President Trump will implement this half-baked and hateful policy, the implication that 15,000 transgender service members could be discharged immediately is disgraceful. I cannot and will not stand for such bigotry. Every American, regardless of their sexual orientation or gender identity, should be allowed the honor and privilege of serving our great country.

This week I made remarks to the House Rules Committee as I introduced an amendment to the Department of Defense Appropriations Act for 2018.  This amendment would prevent the Pentagon from providing any information about our brave service members and diplomats who vote from abroad to Trump‚Äôs #ShamVotingCommission.   Dozens of states have already identified this commission as a sham and have made the common-sense decision to refuse to send data that would compromise the privacy of their citizens. We must afford the same civil liberties to the brave men and women who serve our nation from overseas.

The American People should feel relieved that the Senate failed to take away their healthcare. But the long fight is not over, now we must work together to improve the ACA.  It's not about parties & partisanship, it's about doing what is right for all people rich, poor, employed, jobless...everyone.  Thank you to @SenJohnMcCain @SenatorCollins and @LisaMurkowski for doing the right thing on healthcare. Congressman Gomez's statement on Trump's Afghanistan announcement: ‚ÄúAs with all things in this administration, President Trump‚Äôs announcement on Afghanistan lacks serious detail. Despite the heavily staged nature of tonight's prime time announcement, the president did not announce any new policy and seemingly commits U.S. troops to Afghanistan in perpetuity. The hallmark of any successful military strategy is the presence of a clear endgame, and I fail to see how we can achieve victory if it is not defined by our commander in chief. It is my sincere hope that our military leaders and the President will work with Congress to find realistic solutions in Afghanistan that protect our homeland while minimizing the number of boots on the ground.‚Äù
